<TEXT>
inmates took over a prison farm sunday and 
seized guards and visitors as hostages news broadcasts said with 
as many as five people killed and up to 20 injured 
television station notisiete said easter was a visiting day and 
about 250 prisoners were holding an estimated 400 people hostage 
including guards other inmates and visiting families with children 
notisiete broadcast reports which were not confirmed by 
officials said three guards and two inmates were killed a private 
radio station national broadcasters information patrol service 
reported that at least two guards and two inmates were killed and 
20 people were injured 
neither report gave any indication of the cause of the uprising 
at the pavon prison farm 12 miles east of guatemala city 
the takeover began early sunday afternoon and continued into the 
night local television and radio stations reported 
witnesses said firefighters and red cross workers were seen 
entering the prison with five stretchers 
prison officials and the national police refused to comment on 
the situation 
television newscasts showed the prison farm surrounded by police 
and soldiers sent from the capital an air force helicopter hovered 
overhead 
notisiete said additional army units were on standby 
the national broadcasters information patrol service broadcast 
an interview with a man identified as marcos antonio morales who 
said he and his wife maria were waiting outside to visit a family 
member when the revolt began 
morales told the radio station his wife was among about 20 
people who were wounded in a gunfight between inmates and guards 
he said his wife was taken to a police hospital and he did not know 
the extent of her injuries 
he said he took his wounded wife into a nearby prison chapel 
where many other visitors sought refuge and where other injured 
were being cared for 
reports said officials tried to bargain with prisoners to get 
them to surrender rifles they grabbed from prison guards and then 
most of the weapons were recovered after a gun battle the reports 
said negotiations were continuing 
notisiete quoted fire department cmdr alejandro giammattei 
falla as saying the inmates demanded to talk with federal human 
rights director gonzalo mendez de la riva and that journalists and 
medical workers be allowed to enter the prison 
