<TEXT>
laotians voted to elect their ruling 
national council for the first time sunday in polling that some 
foreign analysts described as a public relations exercise by 
communist leaders 
a senior laotian official said no major changes will be made in 
the communist autocracy that has governed the country for 13 years 
hundreds were already lined up at polling places at schools 
buddhist temples and government offices in this capital city when 
the polls opened in the morning 
the 18 million eligible voters of this impoverished southeast 
asian nation of 38 million people were electing the supreme 
peoples council the highest state body officials said 121 
candidates mostly communist party members are running for 79 
seats on the body 
the council was established when the communists seized power in 
december 1975 
some foreign analysts said the election is intended to convince 
the world laos was stable and an attractive country for foreign 
investment trade and foreign aid 
in an interview last week thai political scientist sirichai 
sirikai said the election is designed only to consolidate the power 
of the communist hierarchy and convince the world of laos 
political stability 
as he arrived at a temple to cast his ballot sisomphon 
lavansay the chairman of the supreme peoples council was asked 
by journalists about reports of major government changes following 
the election 
there will be no changes he replied adding that the 
council will not select a new premier sisomphon refused to reply 
when asked if he would be retiring 
thailands ambassador to laos and the thai media had quoted 
reports that some elderly officials may retire after the election 
including prime minister kaysone phomvihane 68 acting president 
phoumi vongvichit 80 and sisomphon 72 
however somsavath lengsavad permanent secretary of the 
national election committee had called the election another step 
toward socialist democracy 
he said results from the countrys 4153 polling stations would 
be counted by hand and the final tally would not be known for a 
week to 10 days 
the first nationwide district and provincial elections were held 
last year 
</TEXT>
