millions of soviets filled out ballots providing a 
choice of candidates for the first time sunday in parliamentary 
elections that president mikhail s gorbachev called a triumph for 
his vision of democracy 
however maverick candidate boris n yeltsin running to 
represent moscow in the new congress of peoples deputies claimed 
many people are worried about the possibility of vote fraud and 
ballotbox stuffing he complained that the elections werent 
completely democratic 
moscow polling stations brightly lit and festooned with red 
banners and soviet flags opened at 7 am observers reported light 
voter turnout in the morning but the official tass news agency 
said more people were heading for the polls later in the morning 
voters will elect 1500 deputies of the new 2250member 
congress which later will choose the countrys president and elect 
from its own ranks delegates to a new fulltime supreme soviet 
legislature the congress itself will meet once a year 
official public organizations ranging from the communist party 
to a national association for book lovers are directly electing 
750 delegates to the new assembly 
in sundays voting hundreds of races were being contested for 
the first time in 70 years a major change in soviet politics in 
the past the communist party has allowed only one approved 
candidate to run for each seat 
gorbachev who voted with his wife raisa at a polling station at 
moscows institute of chemical physics told reporters afterward 
the sometimes boisterous campaign was just what the kremlin 
leadership wanted 
the electoral law that we passed has justified our hopes 
gorbachev said it has advanced the political thought and social 
activity of the people and this is what we wanted to achieve 
while it was still saturday evening in the capital voters in 
the soviet far east began casting ballots in voting stations 11 
time zones away 
aboard the orbiting mir space station cosmonauts alexander 
volkov sergei krikalev and valery polyakov were also among the 
first to vote radioing their choice to earth tass said 
the soviet voting age is 18 and about 190 million of the 285 
million soviets are eligible to vote according to the central 
election commission voting is not mandatory and ballots are 
secret tass said 
nearly 180000 polling stations nationwide opened sunday morning 
and will close at 8 pm local time according to tass the first 
election results are expected sunday night but full returns will 
not be known for about 10 days 
