<TEXT>
a dispute over cooking oils is heating up as 
farm state lawmakers and consumer groups join ranks on capitol hill 
in what they say is literally a fight for the hearts of americans 
but underlying it all is a battle that has gone on for months 
between agricultural producers the fight matches us soybean 
farmers against foreign palm and coconut growers 
its a symptom of increased international competition that we 
have today for all products says dan reuwee a spokesman for the 
american soybean association 
so far the dispute has produced legislation as well as a war of 
words in advertisements by both sides 
at issue in congress is a proposal by rep dan glickman dkan 
and sen tom harkin diowa to require more nutritional 
information on food packages to help consumers know what vegetable 
oils are used in products and how much cholesterolraising 
saturated fats they contain 
at issue for producers is their share of the 
multibilliondollar us and international markets for edible 
oils which covers everything from salad dressings cooking oils to 
margarine 
according to the agriculture department soybean oil accounts 
for more 70 percent of the edible oils used in the united states 
while the socalled tropical oils palm palm kernel and coconut 
oils represent 4 percent but internationally tropical oils 
dominate and the industry worries that worldwide sales could suffer 
if the current health scare moves overseas from the united states 
the us farm group by its own admission helped start the 
fight by persuading lawmakers to introduce legislation in 1987 
targeting tropical oils as sources of cholesterolraising saturated 
fats 
wed be lying if we said we havent taken advantage of the 
health issue here to market our crop says reuwee but its 
what any good marketing organization does 
palm growers from malaysia the leading producer of the oil are 
striking back with a campaign to promote their product 
we think were getting a pretty bum rap from statements that 
palm oil raises cholesterol when there isnt any evidence 
whatsoever that this is true says john phipps a spokesman for 
the malaysian oil palm growers association 
the latest development came this month when glickman and harkin 
introduced a new version of the legislation the lawmakers 
complained that some products claim to have no cholesterol or 
are made with 100 percent vegetable shortening although they 
contain cooking oils with high levels of saturated fats 
the american heart association which supports the legislation 
says consumers can reduce the risk of heart disease by lowering the 
amount of saturated fat in their diet 
lard is 41 percent saturated fat by weight palm oil contains 51 
percent saturated fat coconut oil 92 percent sunflower oil 11 
percent corn oil 13 percent olive oil 14 percent and soybean 
oil 15 percent 
in general the legislation would require food labels to clearly 
list all cooking oils contained in the product or disclose detailed 
nutrition information including the amount of total fat 
cholesterol and saturated fat 
the previous bill would have required labels to identify 
tropical oils as a saturated fat glickman and harkin dropped 
that provision in an effort to avoid continued opposition from 
tropical oils producers who blocked the original bill by arguing 
it represented an international trade barrier 
however phipps contends the new legislation still will hurt 
tropical oil producers 
it is safe to say that it does not really help their 
predicament forcing a food company to put palm oil coconut or 
palm kernel oil down as a sole source oil probably would be 
somewhat of a deterrent for food companies says phipps 
he contends that negative publicity already has hurt the 
industry in fact a group called the national heart savers 
association led by a millionaire from omaha neb is conducting a 
national advertising campaign against tropical oils using banner 
headlines of the poisoning of america 
already nearly a dozen large food companies such as general 
mills and pillsbury have announced they have stopped or are phasing 
out the use of tropical oils from their products some products now 
carry labels that say they contain no palm or coconut oils 
palm growers have countered with fullpage ads of their own in 
some of the nations largest newspapers decrying the smear 
campaign against tropical oils the industry also has 
commissioned 30 scientific studies including several at us 
universities on the health effects of palm oil 
last year the food and drug administration opposed labeling 
legislation saying tropical oils contribute less than 8 percent of 
saturated fat intake by american consumers in contrast 7075 
percent of saturated fats in us diets come from consumption of 
meats poultry milk cheese butter and eggs 
</TEXT>
