responsible for injecting cyanide in two grapes imported from chile 
while offering no indication that officials necessarily expect 
to make an arrest fda commissioner frank young said the incident 
which prompted the removal from us grocery shelves of all produce 
from chile could result in prosecution under us laws 
we dont have the exact person who would have done it but we 
do have a lot of information and we can trace back with a paper 
trail to the small producer where this particular crop came from 
young said on the nbc television program meet the press 
we do not know who did it but the person would come under 
the us laws of tampering and tampering is subject to multiple 
years in jail and major tens of thousands of dollars of fines 
said young 
he also defended government action in removing chilean products 
from the us market for several days while intensified inspection 
techniques were worked out with chilean officials and acknowledged 
that there will never be a 100 percent guarantee against such 
tampering in the future 
young said it is crucial for individual consumers to play a 
large role in insuring their own safety by inspecting the fruits 
and vegatables they eat 
when you look at it the us government does one part the 
exporting country does another part the consumers do a third 
part said young 
is visual inspection by a consumer really an effective way to 
reduce risk 
yes it is young replied in the case of fruit you 
should be able to if it is injected in see the needle site and 
see the particular softening at that point its also important 
that in the large fruits like apples to look at the stem and 
blossom areas 
young who also headed fda during the cyanide poisoning of 
overthecounter pain medication in chicago several years ago said 
there are almost always visible signs of tampering 
what i was impressed with is when we looked at all of the 
tampering that weve gone through that even with medicines when 
capsules were involved any consumer that had looked at the dosage 
form would have seen that the capsule was tampered with said 
young 
he denied any suggestion that his call for increased consumer 
awareness amounted to the agency shirking responsibility 
id say that we have with the resources at hand moved these to 
meet a variety of crises and we can do that quite well said 
young on the other hand we cannot do 100 percent safety in the 
case of this inspection we had to do a random sampling that we 
then with a probability a statistical probability say that weve 
got the maximum feasible safety that can be done through 
inspection 
 
