<TEXT>
a former soldier has finally gotten his 
recognition 44 years after he climbed into a bombers open bomb 
bay with no parachute and manually dropped a dozen 250pound bombs 
over nazi germany 
russell lee fisher performed his feat in 20belowzero 
temperatures and thin oxygen at 17000 feet while antiaircraft 
fire exploded around the plane according to records authorities 
say he almost certainly saved the lives of the eightman crew 
the retired civilian army employee and former state commander of 
the american legion received the distinguished flying cross in a 
ceremony saturday 
on march 30 1945 fisher was in a b17 bomber on a mission over 
the city of bremen when a malfunction made it impossible to release 
the planes bombs automatically 
the technical sergeant from thurmont climbed into the bomb bay 
hooked his leg around a small catwalk and began pulling pins that 
released the bombs to plummet into a railroad yard and munitions 
factory 
it happened too fast to be scared no one told me to do it no 
one asked me i just went down because i knew it had to be done 
fisher said before receiving the medal 
